column168: A dock truck was utilized to facilitate this delivery. The normal process for this delivery is to park along the front(North) side of this company (Shapco Printing), unload drums from the truck via a power lift gate. Once the drums are set onto the street the driver at this time carts them up a slight rise onto the sidewalk and into the customers facility. While the driver was in the process of carting the drum up the slight rise to the sidewalk the drum bounced up free of the bottom cart feet and slid downward. The sliding motion of the drum against the feet of the drum cart caused a slight slit in the drum causing the product release. When the drum came to rest is was next to the curb and close proximity to the storm drain grate, the driver at this point heard a slight pressure release from the drum (the slit area)and imediately  rolled the drum so the slit was facing up which isolated the product from leaking.  The duration of the product release was less than 1 minute.  The slit that occured in the drum was approximately 1/8 inch long with a 1/16 inch opening.  The position of the slit in the side of the drum was 10 inches upward from the bottom chime.  With verification from the fire dept, by the time they arrived on scene the product that leaked out had evaporated.  When it was determined safe to move this drum, the slit was plugged with an epoxy compound and moved into the printing facility whereas it was their intent to transfer into another package and use the material.
column169: It is my recomendation to utilize the loading dock at this facility to unload drums (this has not been an option in the past due to other facility conflicting issues). I have also discussed drum handling with this particular driver.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While traveling on Interstate 44 in Joplin, Missouri, a leak was detected coming from the trailer of the Roadrunner Dawes Freight Systems, Inc. vehicle.  Driver immediately pulled into the Petro Truck Stop at Exit 4 off Interstate 44.  Mid-America Environmental of Carthage, Missouri was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  Upon arrival on site, Mid-America Environmental inspected the trailer, and discovered one (1) 55-gallon drum, which had released 3/4 of its contents inside the trailer.  Approximately 2 gallons also released to the asphalt beneath the trailer.  Mid-America Environmental utilized absorbent material to clean the affected trailer floor, contaminated freight, and affected asphalt.  Mid-America Environmental offloaded the majority of freight to access the leaking drum, and overpacked the leaker into one (1) 85-gallon overpack.  The spent absorbent material was placed into three (3) 55-gallon steel recovery drums.  The freight was reloaded, and sent on to its destination.  One (1) 85-gallon overpack, and three (3) 55-gallon steel recovery drums were placed back on the Roadrunner Dawes Freight Systems, Inc. trailer, pending disposition from the shipper.  There were no injuries or exposures reported.
column169: Since the release was accidental, and appears to be related to heavy freight crushing the drum, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  Roadrunner Dawes Freight Systems, Inc. will continue to reinforce safe handling procedures and safety guidelines to all personnel.

column168: According to the information obtained the following is known.  While unloading a trailer at 513 Express Drive in Chicago, IL the BAX Global, Inc., DG Specialist noticed a smell of paint.  Upon further investigation, one box was damaged containing two containers of paint.  The paint was contained to the outside of the box.  The cause of release is unknown at this time.  The waste generated (one box) was removed by BAX Global, Inc personnel from the remaining shipment and placed into a 10-gallon container.  The waste generated will be placed into the DG area until coordination of disposal, which will be handled internally.  The shipper and consignee were notified of the release.  No injuries or exposures were reported.
column169: Since the release was accidental, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  However, BAX Global,Inc. will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and procedures to all personnel.

column168: our driver james summa was driving our oil truck unit westbound on belvider road in port deposit, maryland. it is backwoods, in the country. a deer crossed in   front of him from his left. he hit the breaks and pulled the wheel at the   same time to the right. there is a very low, hardly any shoulder on this   road. the right tire went into the ditch and then back onto the road. the   back end of the truck swerved to the right. the truck then falls and slides   on the passenger side of the truck. no one else was involved. the oil tank leaked from a broken weld, several hundred gallons of dyed fuel oil leaked from the tank. there is   a stream right there where the truck came to rest. the leaked oil ran from   the truck, down the bank of the stream, and into the stream. state police   and maryland department of energy were on the scene.  a clean up   crew/hazmat team was called. the driver went to the hospital, and a medical   center for a post accident DOT drug screen.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: A propane type odor was reported in the railyard. BNSF personnel inspected all buildings and other facilities looking for the odor source. Later in the morning, PSPX 21501 in the railyard was indicated as the odor source. Product odor was detected at ground level emanating from PSPX 21501 and it was isolated in the railyard. BNSF responders inspected PSPX 21501 and determined that possibly some product on the exterior shell may have been the odor source; as valves and fittings appeared secured. Later, shipper contract responders inspected PSPX 21501. These responders found the liquid line/liquid valve approximately 1/4 turn open with the corresponding closure plug 1/2 turn less than tool tight. Responders closed the liquid line vale and tool tightened the plug. All other fittings, along with the outage, were checked by the responders. The outage appeared proper and all other fittings were secure. Responders found no evidence that the product in the liquid state had escaped from PSPX 21501, only the odorous product vapor. Subsequently, the odor was no longer detectable and the response was concluded by 1600 hrs. CST, 11/05/06.

column168: Florida Rock & Tank Lines (FRTL) driver arrived at customer's unloading location and contacted on-site personnel to verify the load would fit within the 90% safe fill capacity.  They indicated load would fit by signing off on our "Product Integrity Form".  FRTL driver began to pump-off product into customer's above-ground tank.  While off-loading last compartment, the tank overfilled.  FRTL driver immediately shut down flow of product.  The excess fuel overflowed into vapor hoses and tubes on FRTL trailer.  The vapor tube pressure release valve opened to relieve pressure and approximately 100 gallons spilled onto the ground.  Customer personnel immediately began cleanup.  All spilled fuel was contained and did not go into any drains or soil.  Customer personnel stuck their tank and realized the veeder root indicator was incorrect by approximately 1000 gallons.  Their overfill alarm also failed to operate.  An additional 15 gallons were spilled when additional pressure was releived from vapor lines.  All cleanup was conducted by customer, Orange County Public Schools.
column169: Customer must ensure product will fit within 90% safe fill capacity before ordering or accepting product.    FRTL has also informed customer that we can not deliver to this location until their equipment has been repaired.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While the Highway Transportation driver was offloading the Ecolab, Inc. product at the above referenced location, the containment tank gauge malfunctioned, which resulted in an overflow of product into the containment structure.  Approximately 450 gallons of product overflowed into the containment structure, which surrounds the tank.  The product was contained within the structure, and did not impact the ground or any surface areas outside the structure.  TAS Environmental Services, Inc. of was contacted to assist in pumping the product from the containment structure.  TAS Environmental Services, Inc. used a vacuum truck to recover the free liquid from within the containment area.  Safety-Kleen of Waco, Texas was contacted to coordinate disposal, in accordance with local, state, and federal regulations.  There were no injuries or exposures reported.
column169: Since the incident was accidental, and appears to be related to a faulty tank gauge, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  Highway Transportation and Ecolab, Inc. will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and safe handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: Shipment was loaded in Elizabeth, NJ, secured and sealed. Normal inspections were done in route the last one being about 180 miles away. No leaks from the trailer were detected in these inpections. Driver pulled through 2 DOT scale houses the last being at Vinton, LA (33 miles away from Port Arthur, TX) no leaks were discovered as the trailer went thorugh the scale. Trailer arrived at Veolia in Port Arthur, TX and while doing a walk around inspection, it was discovered that a small amount of liquid was leaking from the rear of the trailer. Trailer was immediately put into a containment area and decontamination and cleanup was done. 4 drums were discovered leaking around their center rings. It appears they were crushed while loading. Trailer has sealed wood floors which appear to have contained most of the leak. Trailer wood floors have absorbed some of the spill and will be removed and properly disposed of. Transporter is entering this incident into a corrective action process and will be assessing secondary containment adequacies and  retraining employees to reduce the risk of re-occurance. Our best estimates suggest that the possible length of release from the trailer was over about 33 miles in the which only about 4 gallons are unaccounted for.
column169: All Drivers will be retrained cargo securement, package inspection and shipment acceptance proceedures, in route cargeo and equipment inspection, incident reporting.    Secondary containment on trailers will be reassessed for adequacy.

column168: Driver was finishing the unload using air pressure.  He shut down the internal and external valves.  However the air lines still contained the air pressure and needed to be bled off.  He verified the bleed off valve handle was in the closed position.  Went to take the nut off that acts as a cap over of the bleed off valve outlet but was having difficulties.  The customer personnel decided to assist.  Our driver had all of the neccessary protective gear on but the plant person did not.  When they finally got the nut/cap off with a pair of channel locks leftover product trapped in the cavity between the internal and external sprayed out due to the ball valve inside the bleeder valve handle being broken.  The product sprayed onto the plant personnels arm and wrist a a light mist on his face.  Plant personnel was rinsed down immediately and taken to the hospital and was treated and released.
column169: 1.  Test the bleeder valve operation prior to unload or pressuring the trailer.      2.  Train driver's not to let plant employee's assist in unload process if they do not have the proper protective gear on.

The General Car Foreman at CSX Transportation’s Queensgate Yard, in Cincinnati, OH, advised that he received a report of a strong odor coming from a G&TX 44003, load Flammable Liquids, NOS (Crude Sulfate Turpentine). He inspected the car and could not find any sign of liquid product release but there was a definite odor. CSXT’s hazardous material department responded an emrgency response contractor to inspect the car. The contractor reported that there was liquid product under the liquid eduction valve protective cover. The liquid valve plug was less than wrench tight and the valve appeared to be closed. The contractor opened and closed the valve to reseat it and installed the plug wrench tight. The shipper, Terrace Bay Pulp, Inc, was notified of the incident and advised of the source of the product release. The car was forwarded to continue to destination. column168: According to the information obtained the following occurred.  While at a truck stop off of US Route 35 westbound, free product was discovered leaking from the trailer.  The Gallia County Emergency Management Agency, Ohio Environmental Protection Agency and the Springfield Fire Department responded to assess the site.  The Springfield Fire Department applied absorbent material to contain the free liquid on the affected asphalt surface.  The Dow Chemical Company Emergency Response Unit and FEE Corporation of Canal Winchester, Ohio were dispatched to perform the cleanup.  Dow Chemical Company personnel investigated the trailer with assistance from personnel from FEE Corporation.  One, leaking 55-gallon drum was discovered inside of the trailer.  Absorbent material was applied inside of the trailer and additional absorbents were applied outside of the trailer.  The freight was removed from the trailer and the trailer was cleaned.  Seven, 55-gallon drums of contaminated absorbent material were generated as a result of the incident.  The damaged 55-gallon drum was placed into an overpack drum and was placed back on the trailer for shipment.  FEE Corporation transported seven, 55-gallon drums of contaminated absorbent material to their facility in Canal Winchester, Ohio pending disposal coordination.  FEE Corporation returned to the site on Tuesday November 28, 2006 and powerwashed the affected asphalt surface at the request of the Ohio Environmental Protection Agency.  One vacuum truck containing approximately 150 gallon of contaminated water was generated as a result of the powerwashing and was transported by FEE Corporation to their facility in Canal Winchester, Ohio pending disposal coordination.  The Ohio Department of Transportation investigated the site and deemed the cleanup satisfactory.

column168: A Veolia driver noticed some spilled material on the back of his truck while unloading a cubic yard container from the vehicle at the Veolia ten day in-transit facility located in Livonia, MI,  The spilled material is a filtercake sludge that contained 69 ppm PCB's. Apparently, during transportation some liquids settled to the top of the container and leaked down the side. All of the spilled material as well as the contents of the cubic yard box were then transferred to UN 1A2 55 gallon drums. The truck floor was then decontaminated with diesel fuel. Subsequent wipe tests detected no measurable PCB's.
column169: The material, due to the nature of the liquids separating out during transportation, is better suited to be packaged in a container rated for free liquids. This was discussed with the offeor and will be shipped this way in the future.    **NOTE: this material was shipped with the Polychlorinated biphenyls, solid, UN3432 shipping description.  UN3432 is not an available choice when completing this online form.

After loading the cargo tanker w/caustic soda solution, operator failed to secure the dome lid to the cargo tanker after verifying proper loading volume.  Driver conducted pre-trip inspection, but failed to climb onto cargo tanker to verify that operator had secured the dome lid properly for transport.  As driver proceeded out of the facility yard on Possum Hollow Road, climbing up and down hills, material began to move ("sloshing") in the cargo tanker.  As driver turned from Possum Hollow Road onto Horton Road, material began to leak from dome and driver notice the leaking in his mirrors as he drove down Horton Road.  He proceeded to drive to a safe location to stop his vehicle on Horton Road.  He pulled off to the side of the road on Horton, and inspected the tanker.  Since he was only one to two minutes out from the facility, he called the plant for assistance.  Stopping the vehicle from movement and securing the dome mitigated the release.  Fire department and third party contractor for environmental clean-up arrived at the scene to remove all caustic soda material from the roadway.
column169: The only reason for this incident is human error, personnel did not follow-up through with their job requirements for loading a cargo tanker and inspecting it for shipment.  Disciplinary action was taken against both the driver and the operator who loaded the tanker.  Both were retrained on specific procedures for inspection of cargo tankers after loading and prior to transport on the road.

column168: UPS DELIVERY VEHICLE 111396 WAS BACKED INTO UNLOADING POSITION AT A CUSTOMER’S LOCATION WHEN THE DRIVER OPENED THE BULKHEAD DOOR AND NOTICED THE CARGO AREA OF THE VEHICLE WAS FULL OF SMOKE. THE DRIVER MOVED THE VEHICLE TO 3 NEARBY FIRE HYDRANT AND CALLED 911. GALESBURG FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED AND EXTINGUISHED THE FIRE. IN THE DEBRIS AFTER THE FIRE WERE SEVERAL SMALL, SEALED, NON-SPILLABLE LEAD-ACID BATTERIES, WIRED IN SERIES OF FOUR OR EIGHT UNITS. THE BATTERIES WERE MARKED AS ENE-SYS CYCLON, 2-VOLT, 4.5 AMP. column168: Driver was unloading in to a new remote dropping system installed at Loves #69 at Durant, Ok. The location of the spill was out of the view of the driver. The fill pipes were on the passenger side of the truck and trailer. The product came out of a connection that had been installed on the pipe that is connected to the underground tank. The connection was a 4" to 2" reducer with a 2" cap. This connection was installed so the store personnel could take stick readings. The cause of the spill was due to the cap had not been replaced on the connection causing a approx. 100 gallons spill on the concrete drive and on to the city street. The spill was contained by the driver and the Durant fire department using sand and spill pads. D S C out of Sherman Tx. Cleaned the spill area and will take the sand and diesel to a assigned disposial area.
column169: We have instructed this driver to check unloading areas more closely before dropping product in location where new construction has occured. The driver stated the reason he was was unaware of the cap being off was, he took his tank readings from the meter inside the store.

According to the information obtained the following occurred.  While unloading, one leaking 55-gallon drum wad discovered inside of the trailer.  Approximately 55-gallons of free product were released.  The damage to the drum was due to a puncture by the forklift during loading.  Wilson Trucking Corporation personnel applied absorbent material and booms to contain the free liquid inside of the trailer and on the impacted asphalt surface.  H.M.H.T.T.C. Response, Inc. of Carlisle, Pennsylvania was dispatched to complete site cleanup.  H.M.H.T.T.C. Response, Inc. applied additional absorbent material as needed.  The damaged drum was placed into one, 85-gallon overpack drum.  The contaminated absorbent materials and booms were placed into three (3) 30-gallon recovery drums and (3) 55-gallon recovery drums for disposal.  H.M.H.T.T.C. Response, Inc. transported one, 85-gallon overpack drum containing the damaged drum, three, 30-gallon recovery drums and three, 55-gallon drums of contaminated absorbent material to their facility in Carlisle, Pennsylvania pending disposal coordination.  No injuries or exposures were reported.
column169: Since the release was accidental and was related to a forklift puncture during loading, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  However, Wilson Trucking Corporation will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: Florida Rock & Tank Lines driver was enroute from Doraville, GA to Lithonia, GA.  He exited I-285 southbound onto Hwy 78 eastbound.  Driver lost control on the exit ramp and vehicle overturned and caught fire.  Total of 9004 gallons of gasoline were released.  Dekalb Fire Rescue allowed fire to burn and consume all product.  Florida Rock & Tank Lines' driver did not survive vehicle crash and fire, but fatality was not a direct result of the hazardous material.
column169: Drivers must slow to a safe speed on exit ramps.  All Florida Rock & Tank Lines drivers go through a defensive drive course which covers this topic, plus an entire chapter on rollover prevention.  This topic will be reviewed and reinforced in all safety meetings company-wide to increase awareness of this very important issue.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: Florida Rock & Tank Lines driver arrived at customer delivery location and prepared to deliver products to customers' underground tanks.  As she hooked up fittings and hoses for unleaded tank, she noticed that the fitting on the tank was loose.  She unhooked the hose in order to secure and properly seal fitting to tank, but failed to re-hook the hose to the fitting.  She slowly opened trailer valve to unload product, but approximately 5 to 10 gallons spilled and immediately ran into storm drainage ditch.  Three barrels of soil and sod were removed.  Cleanup was conducted by SWS.  SWS will be conducting a test of the area.
column169: Drivers must ensure fittings and hoses are hooked up properly before opening trailer valves.  Florida Rock & Tank Lines drivers are trained to "trace their lines" from tank to trailer before opening valve to ensure correct product is delivered to correct tank and ensure all hook-ups are secure.  These procedures will be reinforced in all safety meetings company-wide.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: Florida Rock & Tank Lines driver was unloading at customer location, a retail gas station.  He failed to verify product would fit within 90% safe fill capacity.  Driver unloaded one compartment into tank 2, then proceeded to hook the next compartment up to tank 1.  While unloading into tank 1, product began to escape from tank 2.  (Tanks 1 & 2 are manifolded together.)  Approximately 10 to 15 gallons was released and went into grass/dirt area.  CCG responded to scene for cleanup.
column169: Drivers must always ensure product will fit in tanks within 90% safe fill capacity, which is Florida Rock & Tank Lines policy.  This incident will be reviewed in all safety meetings company-wide to re-inforce the importance of verifying product will fit.

PKG WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING IN THE HUB 2NDARY BY THE IMMEDIATE SUPERVISOR. WITHOUT TOUCHING THE WET PKG HE NOTIFIED THE DMP AND A 12 HR RESPONDER ARRIVED DONNING THE PROPER PPE (INCLUDING SILVER SHIELDS). AFTER REFERRING TO THE DECISION TREE AND   APPROPRIATE RESPONSE SHEET (CLASS 8) THE RESPONDER CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP THE SPILL. NEXT THE RESPONDER TRANSPORTED THE CONTAINED PKG AND CONTAMINATED MATERIALS TO THE DMP PROCESSING AREA. UPON FURTHER INSPECTION THE RESPONDER ACERTAINED   THE CONTAINER CAP (1 OF 1) WAS LOOSE, CAUSING APPROX. 12 OZ OF SPILLAGE. THE REMAINING LIQUID WAS SOLIDIFIED AND CONSOLIDATED WITH THE OTHER CONTAMINATED DEBRIS INSIDE A GREEN DMP BAG. THE BAG OF WASTE WAS DISPOSED OF THROUGH THE DMP USING THE   PROPER HAZ-MAT DISPOSAL PROCEDURE. THE RESPONDER WORE REQUIRED PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT (PPE). FOLLOWED THE DECISION TREE AND APPROPRIATE RESPONSE SHEET, CLEANED UP AND REMOVED THE SPILL SAFELY.

column168: Product overflow occured due to non-working gauge on storage tank. Driver shut down pump and was instructed to brake hoses at the end of the trailer. Hoses were filled with product due to back pressure and upon brakedown product sprayed on driver. Driver was wearing PPE but due to the pressure product dripped down inside of gloves and got on his arms. Driver stripped of PPE and proceeded to showers. Driver was instructed by dispatch to seek in-house medical attention and none was available. Driver proceeded to motel to shower once again. Driver was sent to clinic upon arrival back at terminal. Driver had skin irritaion and lost the hair on his lower arms. He was released to return to duty by attending Physician.
column169: Incident is still under investigation by Safety and Risk Management departments.

column168: THE PALLET CONTAINING THE HM WAS SRAGGER ON THE DOCK.  A DOCKWORKER WAS UNLOADING A LARGE METAL PIECE OF FREIGHT FROM A TRAILER.  AS HE PULLED THE FREIGHT ALL THE WAY OUT OF THE TRAILER AND STARTED TO PUSH IT FORWARD, HE HIT THE PALLET CONTAINING ME HM CAUSING THE METAL PIECE AT FRIEGHT TO PUNCTURE OUT OF THE 5 GALLON CANS OF HM ON THE PALLET.  THE DOCK WORKER IMMEDIATELY LAID THE 5 GALLON CAN ON ITS SIDE TO STOP THE LEAK.  WE THEN PALCED THE LEAKING CAN ON A PALLET WITH CARDBOARD AND ABSORBANT.  CT WAS THEN PLACED IN A RECOVERY DRUM.
column169: AFTER THE CLEANUP, WE HELD A DOCK MEETING AND DISCUSSED THE SPILL AND WHAT WE COULD HAVE DONE TO ELIMINATE THIS TYPE OF SPILL.  THE CREW CONCLUDED THAT THE BEST TO ELIMINATE THIS TYPE OF SPILL WAS TO LOAD AND SECURE ALL HM& NOT SRAGE THEM.  BUT IN THE CASE WHERE THEY MUST BE SRAGGED, WE MUST PUT PALLET AROUND THE FREIGHT TO PROTECT IF ON THE DOCK UNTIL IT CAN BE LOADED.    THE DOCKOWRKER CAUSING THE SPILL WILL BE SUSPENDED FROM SUE OF THE FORKLIFT FOR 30 DAYS AND WILL BE RECERTIFIED UON HIS COMPLETION OF THE SUSPENSION.

column168: Our driver was preparing to make a bulk delivery of diesel fuel to the above ground storage tank at Black River Produce in No. Springfield, VT. The unloading area is sloped toward the rear of the trailer when parked. In error, our driver opened all compartments and vents at once which allowed the diesel fuel to run to the rear of the trailer and go out the vapor line and spill on the ground. Our driver immediately closed the vents and applied clay aborbants to spill. The spill was contained on blacktop. Environmental Products and Services of Vermont was contracted to cleanup the blacktop.     Please note that as there was no actual "package failure" (the vents worked as designed), I completed Part III with info that seemed to be appropriate.
column169: Driver had made successful deliveries to this location before. Driver retrained on proper delivery procedures for unloading on unlevel ground.

column168: WHILE DRIVING UP A STEEP HILL ON A COUNTY GRAVEL ROAD, THE TRUCK STALLED OUT ON A HILL.  TRACTOR/TRAILER ROLLED BACKWARDS AND JACKKNIFED, BREAKING THE TRAILER AWAY FROM THE TRACTOR RESULTING IN TRAILER, PUNCTURING THE TOP OF THE TRAILER WITH THE FRAME RAIL OF THE TRACTOR CAUSING THE RELEASE.  EMERGENCY AND CLEAN-UP PERSONNEL WERE CALLED IMMEDIATELY.  ALL CRUDE OIL SPILLED WAS CONTAINED IN A DITCH RUNNING DOWN ALONG THE ROAD.  THE ENVIRONMENTAL REMEDIATION COMPANY COMPLETED EVACUATION OF CONTAMINATED SOILS AND BACKFILLED THE DITCH PER COUNTY AUTHORITY DIRECTIONS.
column169: WE HAVE INSTITUTED A NEW SAFETY PROGRAM AND PROCEDURES FOR HANDLING EMERGENCIES DURING STEEP CLIMBS.  IT HAS ALSO BEEN ADDED TO THE NEW HIRE TRAINING.

column168: ON 11/08/2006 BETWEEN 7-7:30AM, A MILER TRUCK DRIVER, MR JOHN WHITE PULLED AWAY FROM TRUCKLOADING BAY "B" AFTER LOADING HAD FINISHED, BUT WHILE STILL CONNECTED. IT RIPPED OFF THE SAFETY CAGE AND DAMAGED THE LOADING HOSE, IT ALSO CAUSED SOME DAMAGE TO THE DOME LID ON THE CARGO TANK.  THE DRY DISCONNECT MALE FITTING WAS TORN OFF FROM THE THREAD ON THE DOME LID NIPPLE, WHILE STILL COUPLED TO THE FEMALE END OF THE LOADING HOSE AND THUS STILL OPEN. ACID IN LOADING HOSE SPRAYED ON THE ROOF AND DRIPPED DOWN ON THE CONTAINMENT AREA. A SMALL AMOUNT (2 GALS) GOT ON THE ASPHALT AREA AND WAS QUICKLY NEUTRALIZED WITH SODA ASH.  THE VENT HOSE WAS TORN LOOSE FROM THE CHICAGO (CROWS FOOT) FITTING.  OUR PROCESS TECHNICIANS INSTALLED A CAP ON THE NIPPLE ON THE CARGO TANK'S LOADING FITTING.  MILLER MECHANICS WERE CALLED OUT TO REPAIR THE TRUCK.  THEY BROUGHT AND INSTALLED A NEW DOME LID.  ANOTHER TRUCK WAITING IN LINE WAS SPRAYED WITH NITRIC ACID DRIPPING FROM THE ROOF. MILLER DRIVER MR JOHN WHITE SAID THAT A HAND SIGNAL FROM PROCESS TECHNICIAN, MR TRAVIS BROWN MADE HIM CONSTRUE IT AS THE GO AHEAD SIGNAL TO PULL HIS TRUCK OFF.  MR TRAVIS BROWN SAID THAT HE GAVE A HAND SIGNAL TO TRIMAC DRIVER, MR JAMAL DORSEY, TO PULL AWAY, FROM BAY "C" WHERE EVIDENTLY MR WHITE AND MR DORSEY WERE CHATTING A REPLAY OF OUR VIDEO CAMERA RECORDING SHOWS THAT AS SOON AS MR TRAVIS BROWN STEPPED  ON THE GANGUAY TO DISCONNECT HOSES FROM THE MILLER CARGO TANK, ON BAY "B", MR WHITE'S TRUCK IS SEEN PULLING AWAY.  MR WHITE ADMITTED THAT HE DIDNT LOOK TOWARDS THE GANGWAY NOR TO THE WHEEL CHOKES.  MR WHITE DID NOT BLAME TRAVIS DURING HIS INTERVIEW.

column169: ON THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCSR), SHIPPERS ARE IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED OF ALL HAZMAT RELEASES. FOR NON-ACCIDENT RELEASES (A.K.A. PACKAGE OR CLOSURE DEFECTS), WHERE POSSIBLE, SHIPPERS (RESPONSIBLE PARTY) ARE REQUESTED TO RESPOND, REPAIR AND REMEDIATE. BY IMMEDIATELY INVOLVING THE SHIPPER, IN-DEPTH KNOWLEDGE OF THE RELEASE CAUSE IS GAINED BY THE SAME ORGANIZATION THAT CAN IMPLEMENT PROCESS CHANGES TO PREVENT RECURRENCE. AFTER EACH NAR INCIDENT, KCSR PROVIDES OUTREACH TO THE SHIPPER TO HELP INVESTIGATE ROOT-CAUSE FACTORS FOR CORRECTION. FOR NON-ACCIDENT RELATED RELEASES, THE SHIPPER SHOULD BE CONTACTED DIRECTLY FOR DETAILS ASSOCIATED WITH ACTIONS TAKEN TO PREVENT RECURRENCE.

column168: On Saturday, November 25th at 1730 hours a CSX Mechanical Department employee working in Hamlet Yard observed inbound Tank Car GATX23 156 (Load - Methanol) dripping product from the bottom outlet area. CSX Management immediately implemented their emergency response plan and isolated the railcar. Chemtrec was informed of the release (report number 11252006006) and requested to notify the shipper, Chemserve Terminal. Hepaco Environmental was contacted to respond and secure the container. Once on site Hepaco representatives found the following exceptions: Top Operated Bottom Outlet Valve loose 3 turns; Bottom Outlet Cap loose 1 turn; Top Operated Bottom Outlet Valve Packing Gland Nut loose 1 turn. Hepaco properly secured the container and the car was released to destination. Approximately one gallon of product was lost.  Cause Code: 148  NARRI: 5 (5+3+0) x (2+0) = 80

column168: Driver had stopped at our operating center while taking a break enroute to the consignee.  When he got up from his break, he noticed some product under the front dolly legs of the cargo tank.  He put spill pad and bucket under it.  The product seemed to be solidifying, however, which would not be typical of this product. Very possible that it may have been some prior product that got into the insulation of the cargo tank when a washout cap was not tight.  With the distance the trailer still had to go, we decided to err on the side of safety and transfer the product to a different trailer.
column169: Not sure of the exact cause of this incident.  No problems were detected on the trailer. The most likely cause was a loose front washout cap on a prior load which means a prior driver did not follow procedure by ensuring that the washout caps were tight during his pretrip inspection.

column168: During normal switching operations, UTLX 200582, loaded with Hydrogen Peroxide Aqueous Solutions, was found leaking from the top of the car by CSXT’s switch crew. The car was isolated and the shipper, Degussa Corporation, from Theodore, AL., was contacted. The shipper, of Degussa, said he would send a person to the yard to repair the car. When the representative from Degussa arrived at the car he found the Breathing Membrane (not a Breathing Stone) had dry rotted and allowed the product to splash out from the top of the car. He replaced the Membrane and the car was released to move forward in transportation.    Cause Code: 662    NARRI: 2(5+5+O)x(2+O)=40

When driver returned to terminal and was taking driver equipment out of trailer he noticed an unusual smeel in his trailer. Further investigation discovered that a pallet that he had picked up at his last stop and been pushed up into the pallet staged in front of it. As a result a pail that was staged on the pallet was slightly punctured contributing to the unintentional release. Spilled material that had not evaporated was cleaned with absorbent and placed into a recovery container along with the damaged pail.

column168: Driver arrived at delivery location and hooked his hose to the satellite drop site and started the delivery.  This station was having some concrete work done.  Unknown to the driver the satellite drop site was disconnected and not locked out the new drop site was under tarps where the new concrete was poured.  After a few minutes product was noticed under the tarps, the tarps were pulled back and the mistake was discovered.  The driver then finished unloading the product into the correct site.  A spill response team was called in and product was pumped out from around the tank basin.  The remediation process is proceeding under the guide lines of Minnesota’s MPCA. MPCA SPILL #16651

column168: ACFX 87180 WAS LOADED BY PRAIRIE HORIZON ON 11/9/2006 AND RELEASED TO THE RAILROAD.   THE RAILROAD PICKED IT UP ON 11/11/2006  ON THE PHILLIPSBURG TO GOODLAND JOB FOR TRANSPORTATION TO THE INTERCHANGE AT LUNOR COLORADO WITH UP.  THE CAR WAS DELIVERED TO THE INTERCHANGE ON 11/14/2006 - 11/16/2006 A LOCAL ELEVATOR OPERATOR SMELLED ALCOHOL WHILE WALKING HIS YARD TRAIL & NOTIFIED THE RAILROAD & LOCAL EMS PERSONNEL. THE LOCAL EMS MANAGER RESPONDED IMMEDIATELY  AND IDENTIFIED A VERY SMALL PORTION WAS LEAKING ONTO THE GROUND AS IT WAS A WARM DAY AND MOST OF THE ETHANOL WAS EVAPORATING. HE PLACED A HAZMAT CONTAINMENT SYSTEM UNDER THE LEAKING TRUCK TO CONTAIN ANY FURTHER LEAKS. THE SHIPPER DISPATCHED AN EMPLOYEE WHO CHANGED THE OUTLET GASKET WHICH CONTAINED THE LEAK.  THE DISCHARGE VALVE WAS NOT PROPERLY AND COULD NOT BE SEALED SO THE TANK WAS OFF LOADED AT THE PLANT.
column169: THE RAILROAD IS LIMITED BECAUSE WE ARE NOT A PARTY TO THE LOADING PROCESS BUT I BELIEVE IT WOULD BE EXTREMELY IMPORTANT FOR LOCAL EMS RESPONSE TEAMS TO HAVE ACCESS AND TRAINING TO NON SPARKING (NON METALIC) TOOLS AND TRAINING IN THERE OPERATION SO THEY COULD TIGHTEN THE DISCHARGE VALVE AT THE VERY LEAST IN AN EVENT LIKE THIS.

column168: Florida Rock & Tank Lines driver loaded load of sulfuric acid in Bartow, FL and headed towards Fernandina Beach Florida for delivery.  He stopped at the rest area off I-75 nearest exit 307 and noticed a spill alongside the trailer.  Driver estimated spilled amount at 2 gallons and attempted to clean up the spill with water.  Florida Highway Patrol officer arrived and called the fire department.  Florida Rock & Tank Lines personnel also responded to scene.  Driver admitted he forgot to close the air valve and manual safety valve on trailer, which means product could have been leaking during transit from Bartow to Bushnell.  Total product loss estimated between 2 to 15 gallons based on amount loaded and amount delivered to customer.  SWS responded to scene and performed cleanup.
column169: Florida Rock & Tank Lines driver terminated for lack of regard for product he was hauling and severity of the situation.  All company drivers who use this type of trailer or haul this product will receive additional refresher training on correct operation and procedures for equipment and product.

column168: PETRONS TRANSPORT WAS TRAVELING DOWN HWY 183 NEAR MUSTANG RIDGE TX ON A 4 LANE HWY.  WHEN A PICK UP TRUCK MADE A U-TURN ACROSS TWO LANES OF TRAFFIC DIRECTLY IN FRONT OF OUR TRANSPORT.  THE TRANSPORT STRUCK THE PICK UP AND OVER TURNED. THERE WAS NO LOSS OF PRODCUT OR VAPOR.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES.
column169: WE DEAMED THE ACTIONS OF OUR DRIVER TO BE CORRECT.  THE ACCIDENT WAS DEAMED UNAVOIDABLE.  ALL SAFETY SYSTEMS ON THE TRANSPORT WORKED.  THERE WAS NO LOSS OF VAPOR OR PRODUCT AND ALL MATERIAL WAS RECOVERED FROM THE TRANSPORT.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: Florida Rock & Tank Lines driver arrived at customer delivery location to deliver full load of High Sulfur Diesel, and checked in with the site attendant who indicated the tank currently contained 1089 gallons and would hold our load within 90% safe-fill capacity.  Driver began to pump off product into their above-ground tank.  When 6500 gallons had been pumped off, the tank overfilled and approximately 5 gallons spilled into concrete containment area.  Driver immediately shut off flow of product.  Customer took full responsibility for spill and clean-up.
column169: Customer must ensure product will fit within 90% safe-fill capacity before ordering product and before authorizing carrier to unload product.

column168: Florida Rock & Tank Lines (FRTL) driver arrived at customer location to deliver load of Ultra Low Sulphur Diesel into customers' above-ground tank.  No one from customer site was available to sign our Product Integrity Form, indicating load would fit within 90% safe-fill capacity.  FRTL dispatch called BP and their representative verbally approved pump off of product.  Tank overflowed when we had approximately 150 gallons left, and 5-7 gallons spilled onto hard surface.  No product ran into grass or soil.  All was contained on hard surface.  BP representative took full responsibility for spill.  FRTL personnel responded to scene to aid in clean-up.
column169: Customer must always ensure product will fit within 90% safe-fill capacity before ordering product and before authorizing product to be unloaded.

column168: Driver was in #3 lane w/b on SR-134 going approximately 40 mph. A passenger vehicle was going in the same direction, the driver looked away for a moment or two. When she looked back, a car in front of her was slowing down, she panicked, swerved into the carpool lane, struck the wall, then the drivers side of the silver car she was trying to avoid. She continued out of control striking a black car which then struck our truck. The black car struck the truck a couple of times. The last time seemed to have been when it struck the underside of the trailer ripping the piping right at the Internals. The internal housing was sheared almost even with the belly of the trailer. The valves held most of the fuel back. They had been moved some by the accident, allowing a small amount of fuel to leak. The Fire Department were able to move the valve slightly stopping the leak.
SOUND & SURFACE CK ALERTED EMPLOYEE TO UNDECLARED SHIPMENT.  PACKAGE DID NOT DISPLAY THE ORM-D MARKING BUT CONTAINED AEROSOL CANS.

column168: Unit 2472 went in for annual monthly service and also the pump plumbing needed service as well. The shop disassembled the pumps plumbing for service and notified our dispatch center of the service. Dispatch made notification of the service for that day but failed to note it for the next day of service. The truck was dispatched the next day with the failed plumbing. Dispatch overlooked the out of service plumbing documentation. Driver arrived at the unload point and was unaware of the disasembled plumbing. Driver started the unloading process but was unable to stop the 100-gallon release that occured during this unloading incident because he was unaware of the disasembled plumbing.
column169: A detailed analysis that addresses the root cause of this incident will be shared with all shop foremans and shop personnel. Also a procedure change has been implemented to inform the dispatch department on a daily basis to ensure that dispatch is informed daily of an out of service pump on a unit.

column169: ON THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCSR), SHIPPERS ARE IMMEDIATLEY NOTIFIED OF ALL HAZMAT RELEASES.  FOR NON-ACCIDENT RELEASES (A.K.A. PACKAGE OR CLOSURE DEFECTS), WHERE POSSIBLE, SHIPPERS (RESPONSIBLE PARTY) ARE REQUESTED TO RESPOND, REPAIR AND REMEDIATE.  BY IMMEDIATELY INVOLVING THE SHIPPER, IN-DEPTH KNOWLEDGE OF THE RELEASE CAUSE IS GAINED BY THE SAME ORGAINZATION THAT CAN IMPLEMENT PROCESS CHANGES TO PREVENT RECURRENCE.  AFTER EACH NAR INCIDENT, KCSR PROVIDES OUTREACH TO THE SHIPPER TO HELP INVESTIGATE ROOT-CAUSE FACTORS FOR CORRECTION. column168: After positioning UTLX 92238 at the BNSF repair track for repairs to the top running board or grating assembly around the protective housing cover area; a BNSF employee reported product odor emanating from this tank car. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder inspected UTLX 92238 and found one vapor angle valve and one liquid angle valve not fully closed by 1/4 turn. In addition, the 2 inch plug to the vapor valve was not applied. Responder closed the open valves, applied and tool tightened the vapor valve plug. Afterwards, a slight product odor was still detectable. Responder also found the gauging device housing cover not applied and laying within the protective housing area. The packing gland nut (PGN) to the open gauging device was 1/2 turn loose. Responder tool tightened the PGN and applied the gauging device housing cover. After the gauging device was secure, no further product odor was detectable and the responder concluded that the open gauging device was the leak source.
column169: Ensure shipper’s pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: BNSF inbound train inspection in the railyard revealed UTLX 41087 dripping product from the bottom outlet cap (BOC). BNSF responder reported finding the bottom operated bottom outlet valve (BOV) slightly open (seal ULINE 2121001 removed and replaced with BNSF 06157823 seal after securement completed). The responder closed the BOV and dripping ceased. Afterwards, the responder removed the BOC and drained all accumulated product from the cap. The BOC was reapplied and tool tightened. UTLX 41087 was monitored and after no further evidence of product drips from the BOC, UTLX 41087 was released to proceed to its destination. All spillage evaporated.

column168: During a routine inspection of BNSF fuel tank cars, the BNSF Director Hazardous Material discovered ATSF 98601 dripping residue product from the bottom outlet cap (BOC). The BOC was immediately tool tightened (112 turn) which eliminated further drippage. The top operated bottom outlet valve (TOBOV) was then checked and this valve’s operating rod was found to be 1/2 turn open. The TOBOV was closed. Securement was completed by 1349 hrs. CST, 11/26/06. Afterwards, the BOC was removed to check the integrity of the BOC gasket and it was found to be in good condition. The BOC was reapplied and properly tool tightened. The BNSF inspector/responder wiped the small amount of spillage that landed on a tie center under the BOC. The responder also wiped the BOC and the BOC reducer plug chain assembly. All cleaning material was properly disposed of at the on-site petrochemical recovery drum.
column169: BNSF training and facility review imminently scheduled for the BNSF Gillette facility to eliminate future securement deficiencies on outbound residue fuel tank cars shipments.

column168: THE EVENT CONSISTED OF THE TRANSPORTATION OF RIFLE SCOPES CONTAINING TRITIUM (H-3) FROM OUR MAIN FACILITY BY SECURITY PERSONNEL TO A FIRING RANGE (SEVERAL MILES AWAY) FOR PRACTICE, AND RETURNING THE SCOPES TO THE STATION.  THERE WAS NO PACKAGE FAILURE OR RELEASE OF RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL.  THE SCOPES WERE PACKAGED IN APPROPRIATE GENERAL DESIGN PACKAGING. THE PACKAGES WERE NOT MARKED "UN2911" AS REQUIRED.  NO FORMAL SHIPPING PAPERS WERE REQUIRED FOR THIS TYPE OF SHIPMENT.    THE EVENT OCCURRED BECAUSE STATION PERSONNEL INCORRECTLY ASSUMED THESE DEVICES DID NOT MEET THE DEFINITION OF "IN COMMERCE", THUS FULL COMPLIANCE WITH THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL TRANSPORTATION REGULATIONS (49 CFR) WAS NOT ACHIEVED.
column169: THIS EVENT WAS SELF-IDENTIFIED BY STATION PERSONNEL AND ENTERED INTO THE STATION'S FORMAL CORRECTIVE ACTION PROGRAM.  THE SHIPMENT OF THESE SCOPES WAS SUSPENDED PENDING COMPLETION OF CORRECTIVE ACTIONS.  THE FOLLOWING CORRECTIVE ACTIONS HAVE BEEN COMPLETED:    1.  DEVELOPMENT OF A JOB AID DIRECTING CONFORMANCE TO DOT REQUIREMENTS FOR SHIPMENT        OF THESE DEVICES, INCLUDING THE REQUIREMENT FOR PACKAGE MARKING.    2.  TRAINING OF APPLICABLE PERSONNEL IN ACCORDANCE WITH 494CFR172 SUBPART H.    3.  THIS EVENT WAS ALSO DISCUSSED  WITH THE NUCLEAR REGULATORY COMMISSION (NRC)       DURING THE STATION'S RECENT BIENNIAL INSPECTION OF RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL       TRANSPORTATION ACTIVITIES.    THE FOLLOWING ACTIONS WILL BE COMPLETED BY 1-15-07:    1.  A TRANSMITTAL TO THE NUCLEAR INDUSTRY OF A NOTICE MAKING THEM AWARE OF THIS  ISSUE TO ENSURE APPROPRIATE DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION REGULATION COMPLIANCE.

A BNSF TRAIN CREW MEMBER REPORTED A "CHEMICAL ODOR"  IN THE RAILYARD.  YARD OPERATIONS WERE IMMEDIATELY HALTED AND INBOUND BNSF TRAINS WERE HELD OUT.  INSPECTION IN THE RAILYARD FOR THE ODOR SOURCE BY BNSF RESPONDER REVEALED AMCX 25808 WITH PRODUCT ON THE SIDE SHELL EMANATING FROM THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING AREA.  THE BNSF RESPONDER REPORTED THAT THE LIQUID VALVE AREA WAS THE SOURCE OF PRODUCT RELEASE.  BNSF CONTRACT RESPONDERS  CONFIRMED THAT THE 3 INCH CLOSURE PLUG TO THE LIQUID VALVE WAS LOOSE AND THIS PLUG WAS TOOL TIGHTENED; WHICH ELIMINATED FURTHER PRODUCT RELEASE.  THE VALVE ITSELF APPEARED CLOSED.  RESPONDERS CLEANED SPILLAGE FROM THE PORTECTIVE HOUSING AREA AND THE SIDE SHELL WITH CITRUS CLEANER AND RAGS.  NO PRODUCT IMPACTED THE GROUND.  THE INTACT PROTECTIVE HOUSING COVER SEAL INEOS015197 WAS REMOVED AND REPLACED WITH A SEAL IDENTIFIED AS SRS000207.  FULL RAIL OPERATIONS RESUMED BY 0520 HRS. CST, 11/23/06.  FIVE BNSF TRAINS WERE IMPACTED BY THE OPERATIONAL INTERRUPTION.

column168: ON 11/06/2006, ROLLOUT SIDE COLLISION IN THE BNSF LAFAYETTE RAILYARD DAMAGED SCMX 4338.  THERE WAS NO RELEASE OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AT THE TIME OF THIS INCIDENT.  LATER, ON 11/27/2006, AS BNSF MECHANICAL PERSONNEL WERE PREPARING TO REPAIR THE DAMAGE TO SCMX 4338, THEY REPORTED A FAINT PRODUCT ODOR EMANATING FROM SCMX 4338.  SCMX 4338 WAS CORDONED OFF.  BNSF CONTRACT RESPONDER REPORTED THAT THE LIQUID VALVE WAS CLOSED, BUT THE CORRESPONDING CLOSURE PLUG WAS LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT.  THE RESPONDERS ATTEMPTED TO REMOVE THE THREADS.  THIS INDICATED TO THE RESPONDERS THAT PRODUCT WAS BYPASSING THE CLOSED VALVE.  RESPONDERS TIGHTENED WHICH STOPPED ANY FURTHER PRODUCT RELEASE.  RESPONSE WAS CONDLUDED BY 2000 HRS. CST, 11/27/06.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED TO REPAIR OR REPLACE THIS FAULTY LIQUID VALVE.  THE PRODUCT IN SCMX 4338 WAS TRANSFERRED INTO ANOTHER SUITABLE TANK CAR WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT ON 12/21/06.

column168: A BNSF train crew, after completing a roll-by inspection of a passing BNSF train, reported to the other train crew that their entrained FPAX 931031 was possibly leaking product onto its side shell. The train with FPAX 931031 was stopped on the main track at the BNSF Dalies, NM station location awaiting further inspection. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder inspected FPAX 931031 finding that the 165 psi frangible disc had ruptured, which allowed some product to escape from this orifice. No liquid product was found, only dried white powdery residue on the top and sides of this tank car. No product impacted the ground. The responder replaced the ruptured frangible disc with a 100 psi frangible disc, the only frangible disc available in his response vehicle. The responder wiped as much residue product from the top and side shell as he could safely reach. The train with FPAX 931031 was released to proceed at 1405 hrs. MST, 11/18/06. Arrangements were made with the consignee to replace the 100 psi frangible disc with a 165 psi frangible disc and clean the rest of FPAX 931031 after it was unloaded.

column17: DAKOTA, MINNESOTA AND EASTERN RAILROAD CORP.
column168: DAKOTA, MINNESOTA & EASTERN RAILROD TRAIN #EAUCC-22 WAS EASTBOUND AT A RECORDED SPEED OF 24 MPH AT MILEPOST 157.75 WHEN IT ENCOUNTERED BROKEN RAIL.  SEVEN TANK CARS CONTAINING ETHANOL DERAILED WITH ALL BUT ONE CAR LEAVING THE RAIL.  THE FINAL CAR IN THE DERAILMENT CAME TO REST IN AN UPRIGHT POSITION ON A WOOD CONSTRUCTION BRIDGE.  THE TRAIN CREW BEGAN AN INSPECTION OF THE UNDESIRED EMERGENCY.  THEY SMELLED ETHYL ALCOHOL (ETHANOL) AND CONTACTED DISPATCH AND THE LOCAL EMERGENY RESPONSE TEAM.  AS INFORMATION FROM THE SCENE WAS RELAYED THROUGH DISPATCH, FORCES WERE DISPATCHED INCLUDING, LOCAL FIRE, AMBULANCE, LAW, DM&E'S HAZ-MAT MANAGER, MINNESTOA REGIONAL HAZ-MAT RESPONSE, CONTRACT HAZ-MAT RESPONDERS, ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONSE ENGINEERS, AND A RE-RAILING CONTRACTOR.  INITIAL DAMAGE ASSESSMENT INDICATED AT LEAST THREE CARS LEAKING PRODUCT TO THE GROUND.  THE AREA WAS A DRY CREEK BED.  TANK CAR ACFX 200406 WAS ON ITS SIDE WITH THE FILL VALVE BROKEN AND A SMALL PUNCUTRE IN THE MAN WAY COVER.  BOTH OF THESE LEAKS WERE GIVEN A TEMPORARY REPAIR WITH PLUGS AND PLUG AND PATCH MATERIAL.  TANK CAR RTMX 30684 WAS ON ITS SIDE LEAKING A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT FROM THE MAN WAY.  BOLTS WERE TIGHTENED.  TANK CAR GATX 35196 WAS UPRIGHT ON THE TRACK STRUCTURE  AT ABOUT A 20 DEGREE ANGLE WITH A 2 INCH GASH IN THE HEAD SHELL.  PLUGS AND PLUG AND DIKE WERE APPLIED.  DURING OUR SECOND DAMAGE ASSESSMENT, TANK CAR UTLX 46755 WAS NOTED UPRIGHT ON A BRIDGE LEAKING FROM AN UNKNOWN SOURCE.  IT WAS LATER DISCOVERED TO BE THE MAN WAY GASKET.  THE CAR WAS AT AN ANGLE ON THE BRIDGE THAT THE LEAK STOPPED ITSELF PRIOR TO SUNRISE.  EQUIPMENT AND MANPOWER WAS BROUGHT TO THE SITE THROUGOUT THE NIGHT AND EARLY MORNING.  THE CARS WERE MONITORED FOR FURTHER LEAKAGE, AIR MONITORING CONTINUED, AN EVACUATION OF 12 CITIZENS TOOK PLACE.  REMAINING PRODUCT WAS TRANS-LOADED TO RAILCARS.  ALL PRODUCT ON THE GROUND WAS VACUUMED AND SENT TO A DESTRUCTION FACILITY. FINAL TRANS-LOADING WAS COMPLETED ON NOVEMBER 25, 2006 AT 2100 HRS.  TOTAL PRODUCT SPILLED WAS 24,877 GALLONS OF WHICH 11,807 GALLONS WERE RECOVERED AND DISPOSED OF IN ACCORDANCE WITH REGULATIONS.
column169: A SLOW ORDER REDUCING SPEED OF ETHANOL TRAINS OVER JOINTED RAIL HAS BEEN ISSUED ON THE DAKOTA, MINNESOTA & EASTERN RAILROD PROPERTY.    BETTER MAN-WAY GASKETS MAY HELP IN REDUCING LEAKAGE WHEN TANK CARS ARE IN OTHER THAN THE UPRIGHT POSITION.    NOTE:      I AM AWAITING BUILT INFORMATION ON RTMX 30684 TANK CAR.  I HAVE REQUESTED THIS INFORMATION FROM THE CAR OWNER AND THEY HAVE YET TO PROVIDE IT.  THE CAR HAS BEEN DESTROYED.  I WILL SUBMIT ADDITIONAL INFORMATION IN ACCORDANCE WITH 171.16 (c) UPON RECEIPT.

column168: TRUCK APPLIED BRAKES & SWIRVED TO AVOID ANOTHER VEHICLE IN THE ROADWAY. TRUCK ROLLED OVER AFTER TWO MORE STEARING CORRECTIONS. IMPACT ON HIGHWAY CAUSED THE BULK TANK TO BE RIPPED OFF FRAME CAUSING LEAKS AT PIPING AND A FAILURE TO ONE DOME LID.  AREA WAS SHUT DOWN TO TRAFFIC AND FUEL WAS CONTAINED ON SIDE OF ROAD WITH DIRT & NATURAL BLOCKAGE. PRIVATE HAZARDOUS RESPONSE TEAM WAS CALLED TO THE SCENE TO FURTHER CONTAIN & CLEAN UP ROADWAY WITH DRY SWEEP. REMAINDER OF FUEL WAS PUMPED OUT OF EACH COMPARTMENT ONTO ANOTHER FUEL TRUCK. MOST OF THE RELEASE OCCURED IN THE FIRST FEW MINUTES FOLLOWING THE ACCIDENT. THE RELEASES OCCURED FROM A PARTIALLY OPENED DOME LID ON COMPARTMENT 1, A RUPTURED VAPOR LID ON COMP 2, AND FROM BROKEN PIPING/VALVE ON THE BOTTOM OF COMPARTMENT 3.

column168: NO NOVEMBER 17, 2006 APPROXIMATELY 10:00PM, YURY SARRIS, OWNER OPERATOR WITH B-LINE CARRIERS, WAS TRAVELING SOUTH ON INTERSTATE 75 AT MILE MAKER 250 WHEN A HYUNDAI SEDAN WAS HIT FROM BEHIND, AND IS KNOCKED ACROSS A CENTER LANE AND BECOMES LODGED BENEATH OUR TRAILER.  THE B-LINE DRIVER PULLS OVER ON TO THE SHOULDER OF THE ROAD, WHILE THE HYUNDAI SEDAN IS UNDERNEATH THE TRAILER, IT CATCHES FIRE AND EXPLODES.  ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION WE RECEIVED, A LAWN TRACTOR USED TO MOW HIGHWAY MEDIANS, CONTRACTED BY THE FLORDIA DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION, WAS TRAVELING IN THE LEFT LANE ON INTERSTATE 75 APPROX 25 MPH WHEN TWO VEHILCES TRAVELING AT HIGHWAY SPEEDS NOTICED THE LAWN TRACTOR AND BRAKED SUDDENLY TO AVOID HITTING THE LAWN TRACTOR.  A TOYOTA PICKUP REARENDS A HYUNDAI SEDAN WHICH SENDS THE SEDAN INTO OUR TRAILER. SEE ATTACHED NEWS ARTICLE FOR MORE INFORMATION.
column169: RECOMMENDATION:  KEEP LAWN MOWING TRACTORS OFF ALL PUBLIC ROADWAYS AFTER DARK.

column168: Driver was dispatched to pick up an empty ammonium hydroxide trailer from a local washout facility where the trailer was cleaned.  He was to proceed to ChevronTexaco to pick up a load of ammonium hydroxide. Driver arrived at the load rack, connected the trailer, and began the filling operation. During the loading process, Mr. Najar climbed on top of the trailer and detected a smell of ammonia, climbed down and immediately shut down the filling operation. Driver looked at the top of the trailer and noticed vapor coming from an opening on top of the trailer. He returned to the top of the trailer and found a clean out cap on the rear of the trailer was loose. He tightened the cap and climbed down from the trailer. He looked up again and still saw vapor escaping from the top of the trailer, this time from the front. He again climbed up and discovered the front clean out was not installed. Driver installed and secured caps which stopped the release. Once the trailer was deemed secure, loading resumed without further incident.
column169: Suggested Remedial Action:  a)A new SOP involving “Commissioning Ammonium Hydroxide Trailers after Tank Wash” is to be   written, approved by Regional Managers and added to formal list of SOP’s immediately.  b)Ensure that all employees of ASP are given refresher training for ammonium hydroxide loading.   c)Ensure that all employees are given refresher training on reporting requirements for incidents involving anhydrous ammonia and ammonium hydroxide.  d)Ensure that all ASP employees are trained on the new SOP for “Commissioning Ammonium Hydroxide Trailers after Tank Wash.

column168: Ferrellgas Driver, Arnoldo Benitez was driving a Bobtail and noticed a loss of power, was in the slow lane of traffic, turned on 4 way flashers, and looking for a place that was safe to pull over when he was rear-ended by a Transport Truck.  The Transport Truck then swerved to the left and also struck a second vehicle.      Rear end impact damage the meter on the propane cargo tank which caused a minor release of propane.  There was no injury or damage as a result of the release and no cleanup required.  The propane dissipated in the air.
column169: Third party responsible for accident.  Since third party was responsible for damages, we do not have access to the amount of property damage for the other vehicles.

column168: On 11-15-2006 at approximately 0935, DRIVER reported to OIL DISPATCH, that he was driving on the road of 15200 Croom-Airport Road in Upper Marlboro, MD 20772 when his passenger side front tire caught the edge of the roadway and the truck skidded out of control overturning and leaking product from the oil truck tank. I arrived on scene at approximately 10:30 am with an empty oil truck to pump over the remaining oil. I found multiple fire fighting equipment, PG county police cars, and MDE on the scene. The PETRO oil delivery truck was laying on its driver’s side, rear of truck down hill from the road and completely off of the pavement. The weld from the tank was cracked and leaking. MDE cut holes in the side of the container and pumped over the oil from the over turned oil truck. Driver went to the hospital for observations, and submitted to a Drug - Alcohol test, which results, showed no influences.      I spoke to John Myers from MDE oil control and we discussed the weather that was forecast for late in the day and the next day, with thunderstorm and heavy rain expected. John advised me that he would like the oil cleaned up as soon as possible to keep from dispersing the oil and contaminating the wells on either side of the release.    We advised John that Tri-county was here and starting the process of cleaning up.  After about an hour Tri-county still had no equipment on the scene, we spoke to Jeff Molner from MDE and it was determined to have a second cleanup crew on-site. We called Paul over at Atlas environmental services, (we use Atlas in Virginia to do tank work) and asked him if we needed him would he be available to respond. Which he responded he would, I advised him of the size of the release so he could start to get a plan together and I would call him back. Paul from Atlas was called and discussed the size of the response,    We concluded that we would need   1. 1 small tracked excavator  2. 1 bobcat tracked  3. 1 large excavator  4. 8 dump trucks    We continued to have Tri-county ‘s vacuum truck keep cleaning up the liquid product.  When they were through cleaning up the liquid product we released them from the scene. By that time Atlas had 8 dump trucks the bobcat, and small excavator on sight and moving contaminated soil to a staging area to load the dump trucks when the large excavator got on scene.    The excavator arrived around 4:30, which then started to load contaminated soil onto the dump trucks to be taken to their facility until morning when the soil could be taken to a disposal site. The excavation continued until 10:00 pm and all 8 dump trucks had been filled and the street was cleared of debris. We left the scene with Atlas to return in the morning to resume clean up. column169: One of our biggest initiatives here at Petro is to improved our efforts toward making all of our on-road employees safer behind the wheel.  Our Driver Improvement Plan is made up of four basic components:    1·6/8 Hour National Safety Council Defensive Driving Course (DDC 6/8)  2·Targeted Decision Driving Program  3·Specialized “Coaching the Van Driver” and “Coaching the Truck Driver” CDROM programs  4·Other outsourced or district-specific activities and curricula (i.e. our Safety Incentive Program, Monthly Safety Meetings, etc.)     By implimenting this plan with all of our on-road employees, we would directly prevent future recurrences.

WHEN THE SPILL WAS DISCOVERED ROBERT DEAN TOLD THE SUPERVISOR ON DUTY. JUSTIN VOWELS WAS THE SUPERVISOR ON DUTY. JUSTIN CALLED JEFF TURNER FOR INSTRUCTION ON WHAT TO DO. JEFF TURNER IS THE SAFTEY SUPERVISOR, HE INSTRUCTED JUSTIN TO CALL THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE NUMBER TO SEE IF THERE WAS ANY HAZARD TO THE CLEAN UP. THEY SAID IT WAS OK TO CLEAN. THE SPILL WAS ON THE BOTTOM OF THE 55-GALLON DRUM WITH A HOLE THAT IS ABOUT A 1/4 IN WIDE ESTIMATED ABOUNT OF SPILL IS ONE GAL. THE SUCTION OF THE DRUM PREVENTED A LIMITED AMOUT TO DRAIN OUT OF THE DRUM. THIS SPILL APPEARS TO HAVE BEEN CAUSED BY A FORKLIFT THAT PUNCTURED IN FROM UNDERNEATH THE DRUM. THE FORKS WERE ANGLED WRONG AND ALSO BROKE UP THE PALLET THAT THE DRUM WAS ON.

column62: Defective Component or Device; Human Error; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: ON I 1/04/2006, 00:00, CSX TRANSPORTATION HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MANAGER, S. MICHAEL AUSTIN, WAS NOTIFIED BY T/M JASON MCCLURE THAT ULTX 71412 HAD WHAT APPEARED TO BE A STRONG ODOR COMING FROM THE CAR. CSXT HAZ-MAT DISPATCHED HEPACO INC (RICHMOND) TO RESPOND TO THE INCIDENT. HEPACO ARRIVED ON SITE AND DELECTED A SLIGHT ODOR OF TURPENTINE IN THE AREA OF THE CAR. FURTHER INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THE GASKET IN THE MANWA COVER WAS FLATTENED, AND VAPORS WERE BEING RELEASED FROM THE MANWAY COVER. HEPACO REMOVED THE FLATTENED GASKET AND REPLACED IT WITH A NEW GASKET AND SECURED CAR. NO FURTHER EXCEPTIONS WERE NOTED AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION.     CHEMTREC REPORT 11042006002   CAUSE CODE: 209   NARRI: 5(5+1+0)(2+0) = 60

CSX Transportation yardmaster, Mr. Frank Dean, Flint, MI advised CSX Transportation’s Public Safety Coordination Center that a CSX Transportation, Mechanical Department Car Inspector, Flint, MI noted an odor and heard a hissing about GATX 95747 upon its arrival at CSX Transportation yard, Flint, MI. CSX Transportation dispatched Young’s Environmental Services, Inc., Flint, MI. Young’s Environmental Services, Inc., reported at 1845 hours, 11/02/2006, that release of vapor was due to the packing gland nut for the gauge device not being sufficiently tight to prevent release of vapor. They tightened the packing gland nut and leak ceased.  Cause Code 498  NARRI: 5(4±5+O)x(2+O)=90

column168: At 19:27, Jim Briski, Manager Hazardous Materials, CSX Transportation, was contacted by the CSX Transportation, Public Safety Coordination Center. They advised tank car GATX 6458 had been reported leaking from the top while the car was in the CSX Transportation, Rossford, Ohio yard and the car was isolated. A CSXT emergency response contractor, Eagle Construction and Environmental Services, Inc. (ECESI), Findlay, Ohio was dispatched. Chemtrec was notified, report #11092006075. ECESI personnel reported that the fill hole cover gasket was out of place. The fill hole was opened, the gasket was placed into the proper position, and the fill hole cover was closed and properly sealed. The car and the area around the car was decontaminated and the rail car was forwarded to destination.     NARRI: 5 (5+5+0) X (2+0)=100     Cause Code= 232

column168: 11-11-06 at 0455 hrs, Norfolk Sourthern Railroad advised CSX Transportation that one of their trains moving West on track #2 at MP 485, derailed and impacted CSX train Q32511 traveling East on a parallel track. This caused two rail cars (UTLX 208096 & GATX 202155) in the CSX train to derail. UTLX 208096 rolled over on to it’s top shearing off the liquid eduction valve resulting in a release of  1,000 gallons of product. NS RR responded Sunpro to clean up the spill and transfer the remaining product to frac tanks. The consignee, Marathon Petroleum, arranged for motor carrier trucks to deliver their product to destination at Hammond, IN, from the frac tanks. The cause of the derailment was an improperly loaded car in the NS train. This incident was reported to Chemtrec on report #11122006015.  ATARI: 2(5+3+0) (5+O)=8O  Cause code = M204

At 0200 hours, 11/19/2006, CSX Transportation Yardmaster, Wendy Romer, Stanley Yard, Waibridge, OH, contacted the CSX Transportation, Public Safety Coordination Center (PSCC). She advised that GATX 26589 was reported by the “hump crew” to be dripping from the bottom of the tank. She stopped the car in the retarder atop the hump She advised, one CSX Transportation employee had been taken to Bay Park Community Hospital, Toledo, OH. Eagle Construction and Environmental Services, Inc. (ECESI) was dispatched by CSX Transportation, Hazardous Materials Systems personnel. The Center for Toxicology and Environmental Health (CTEH) was contacted by CSX Transportation, Hazardous Materials Systems personnel, requesting their contact with Bay Park Community Hospital personnel. In addition, CTEH personnel contacted the yardmaster. The yardmaster reported five additional employees had requested hospital medical attention. John Siefert, Director-Oiio Division, ECESI and Timothy Mannas, Manager-Hazardous Materials, CSX Transportation inspected GATX 26589 at approximately 0530 hours, 11/19/2006. A dripping was noted at the interface of the inboard end of the “A” end stub sill and the tank car jacket. ECESI employed a “Multi-Rae” detector and it was determined the dripping was water/condensate. All top fittings were inspected and no indication of a release was found. Three additonal tank cars, Residue: Last Contained Vinyl Chloride, Stabilized, were inspected by ECESI, with no indication of a release of material. Messrs. Siefert and Mannas advised local emergency responders on scene. Local emergency responders departed at approximately 0630 hours, 11/19/2006. Stanley Yard traffic had ceasd with initial report of dripping.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Improper Preparation for Transportation; Deterioration or Aging
column168: On November 20th, 2006, 1615 hours, a car inspector noticed UTLX 48206 dripping product from the bottom outlet cap. The car inspector notified Frontier Yard Control, and the TERP Plan was initiated. The tank car was isolated and the PSCC was notified, CSXT HazMat Sentinel, Steve Myers was notifed and CSXT HazMat Mgr., M. Bethge, was also notified. A CSXT HazMat Emergency Response Contractor was called to assist in the response and cleanup of the released product. Sentinel S. Myers, placed a bucket under the bottom outlet valve to contain spilled product and tighten the bottom outlet cap one full turn. This slowed the drippage to 1 drop every two minutes. HazMat Mgr. M. Bethge, upon investigation, found that the internal ball valve was not fully closed. This was due to the operating handle making contact with the stop plate/securement pin plate, preventing the ball valve to close fully. The valve remained open approximately 1/16 to 1/8 inch. Excess wear was noted in the pin/allen bolt that connects the operating handle to the external section of the valve stem. CSXT emergency response contractor closed the bottom outlet valve fully, drained the unloading extention pipe, inspected the 4” cap gasket and the 2” plug threads. All items were found in good order, therefore, re-applied the cap and plug and tightened tool tight and wire sealed the handle back tight to the stop plate to insure that the valve would remain closed. UTLX 48206 was released for disposition.  NARRI: 5(5±3+0)(2±0)—80   Cause Code 148
column169: THE SHIPPER SHOULD DEVELOP PROCEDURES TO CHECK ALL VALVES, FITTINGS AND CLOSURES PRIOR TO OFFERING A PACKAGE FOR TRANSPORTATION.

At 09:2 1 hrs., Train Master, at Barr Yard, Riverdale IL., reports tank car ACFX 79635, load of Isopropyl Acetate, is leaking from the bottom outlet valve cap. The car was isolated and Chemtrec was notified (#1127006003). A CSXT emergency response contractor, Sunpro Services, was called to inspect the car. Once on scene, Sunpro reported that the top operating rod for the bottom outlet valve was open about 3/4 turn. The operating rod packing gland nut and the bottom outlet valve cap were both loose about a 1/4 turn. Sunpro closed the valve, tightened the packing gland nut, and tightened the bottom outlet valve cap. One pint was release. The car was sealed and sent to destination.    Cause Code: 662    NARRI: 5 (5+1+0) X (2+0) = 60

column168: THIS SHIPMENT OF 8 BACK-UP BATTERIES WAS BANDED TO A WOOD SKID AND SHIPPED TO   MEMPHIS VIA OUR FEDEX EXPRESS FLIGHT FROM CALGARY CANADA. UPON ARRIVAL INTO MEM,   THE BANDING APPARENTLY WAS BROKEN AND ONE OF THE BATTERIES FELL AND WAS COMPROMISED IN SUCH A WAY, THAT IT WAS SMOLDERING AND GIVING OFF A HEATED SOURCE   AROUND THE PERIMETER. THE FEDEX SPILL PERSONNEL ADVISED ME OF THE INCIDENT, AND I   ARRIVED TO WORK WITH MY FEDEX ELECTRONICS PERSONNEL AND OUR FIRE SERVICE UNIT TO   ENSURE THE BATTERY PACK WAS OF NO FURTHER DANGER. KEN HOLMAN OF THE LDCAL FAA   OFFICE WAS NOTIFIED ON MONDAY NOVEMBER 27 OF THE INCIDENT, AS WELL AS JANET   MCLAUGHLIN IN THE WASHINGTON, DC FAA OFFICE. THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED AND SENT   A REPRESENTATIVE FROM THEIR LOCAL OFFICE IN MEM TO INSPECT THE SHIPMENT. THE 7   OTHER BATTERIES WERE LATER CONTAINED ON ANOTHER WOOD SKID AND RETURNED TO THE   SHIPPER LOCATION. THE DAMAGED BATTERY WAS HELD PENDING DISPOSAL DISPOSITION.

Residue tankcar GATX 46450 released product at a steady drip from the bottom of the tankcar in the Neff Flailyard in Kansas City, Missouri.Regional Manager Chemical Transportation Safety, was notified and advised Hazmat Response, Environmental Contractor, would inspect the car and make necessary repairs to stop the release. Inspection of the car by representatives of Hazmat Response, Inc. revealed that the top operated bottom outlet valve was partially open as a result of the packing gland nut being loose two full turns. This resulted in a steady drip of product from the bottom outlet valve. The valve was closed, the packing gland nut tightened and the release stopped.

11/29/06: While performing a routine inspection at Conrail’s Bayonne, NJ yard, ERA Hazardous Materials Inspector R.A. Dedow noted a liquid with one drop per minute originating from the top operated bottom outlet auxiliary valve closure plug. Mr. Dedow reported his finding to the Oak Island Yard (Newark, NJ) East End Yard master.  Further inspection by Messrs. R. Gloede, Assistant Superintendent, and R. Caparelli, Manager Car Inspect on and Repair, noted no leak. The bottom outlet was checked and found to be tool tight. Car was moved back and forth to insure no further leakage. No exceptions noted and car forwarded to original destination.  Call out to East Jersey Railroad (EJRR) from which Conrail received the car in interchange with no results. Any additional information obtained will be supplemented to this report.

MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED. AT 06:2OAM, MANAGER COOPER STATED TANK CAR TRLX 26835 WOULD HAVE TO BE MOVED FROM THE YARD LOCATION TO A STUB TRACK LOCATION IN ORDER TO MAKE THE NECESSARY REPAIRS. ANOTHER MANAGER STATED ALL FOUR STUDS THAT SECURE THE LIQUID EDUCTION LINE HAD BEEN SHEERED OF AT THE LIQUID VALVE FLANGE. MANAGER REQUESTED CHEMTREC BE NOTIFIED TO CONTACT THE SHIPPER. DEVELOPED THE WAYBILL SHIPPER, KMTEX, ONLY LOADED THE PRODUCT FOR THEIR CUSTOMER, TOTAL PETROCHEMICALS. CONTACTED TOTAL PETROCHEMICALS AND ADVISED THEY WOULD HAVE TO MAKE ARRANGEMENTS WITH THE LOCAL LANK CAR MOBILE REPAIR SERVICE TO MAKE THE NECESSARY REPAIRS TO THE CAR. UTLX HAS A MOBILE SERVICE OUT OF THEIR SHOP LOCATED IN EL SEGUNDO, CA. ON FRIDAY, DECEMBER 01, 2006, THE UTLX SHOP ADVISED REPAIRS HAD BEEN MADE, AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE LOCAL CCNSIGNEE. CAR TO BE SHOPPED UPON RETURN TRIP.

column168: UNION PACIFIC TRAIN DISPATCHER 40 REPORTED THAT WESTBOUND TRAIN MKSTU 28 HAD CAR UTLX 208283 LEAKING PRODUCT FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR. THE TRAIN WAS STOPPED AT MILE POST 1284. MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY WAS NOTIFIED AND ADVISED HE WOULD CONTACT VIVA ENVIRONMENTAL TO RESPOND. EMPLOYEE REPORTED THAT CONTRACTOR VIVA ENVIROMENTAL HAD INSPECTED THE CAR AND FOUND THE FOLLOWING EXCEPTIONS, 1. LIQUED LINE SECURING CAP LESS THAN WRENCH TIGHT, 2. VAPOR LINE SECURING CAP LESS THAN WRENCH TIGHT, 3. BOTTOM OUTLET CAP LESS THAT WRENCH FIGHT, 4. BLIND FLANGE LOCATED NEXT TO THE LIQUID LINE FOUND TO HAVE WHAT APPEARED TO BE AN IMPROPER GASKET THAT WOULD NOT SEAT. GASKET HAD TO BE MODIFIED TO FIT AROUND THE FOUR BOLT PATTERN TO THE FLANGE. (THIS EXCEPTION WAS FOUND TO BE THE PROBLEM CAUSING THE LEAK. ALL EXCEPTIONS WERE CORRECTED, CAR OWNER OBTAINED FRA MOVEMENT APPROVAL #FRA-06120330 TO MOVE CAR TO DESTINATION FOR OFF-LOADING AND THEN TO A SHOP FOR PROPER GASKET REPLACEMENT. SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED AND ADVISED OF THE EXCEPTIONS THAT WERE FOUND AND CORRECTED. CAR RELEASED TO TRANSPORTATION.

UPDATE: AT 05:00 PM, EMPLOYEE ADVISED THE RELEASE WAS STOPPED, THE PRODUCT WAS REMEDIATED AND THE TANKCAR WAS READY FOR TRANSPORT.
